>Conor McAnally\n| creative_director = \n| starring          = [[Younan Nowzaradan]], MD\n| judges            = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| voices            = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| narrated          = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme         = \n| endtheme          = \n| composer          = David Hamburger\n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| num_seasons       = 8\n| num_episodes      = 110\n| list_episodes     = List of My 600-lb Life episodes\n| executive_producer = Jack Tarantino<br />Cameo Wallace<br />Ron Bowman<br />Jeff Keels<br />Graham Davidson<br />Tom Mireles<br />Jonathan Nowzaradan\n| producer          = Leslie Appleyard<br />Amy Yerrington<br />Dawn Cooper Johnson\n| news_editor       = <!-- Content editor or editors of a current affairs/political show such as Newsnight. -->\n| location          = [[Houston]], Texas\n| cinematography    = Taylor Rudd\n| editor            = Shrader Thomas<br />Jennifer Kovacs<br />Gareth Dawson<br />John Gehrke<br />Knox Hughes\n| camera            = Multi-camera\n| runtime           = 45 Mins (excluding advertisments)(Season 1-4), 85 Mins (excluding commercials) (Season 5-)\n| company           = Megalomedia\n| distributor       = [[TLC (TV network)|The Learning Channel]]\n| budget            = \n| network           = TLC\n| picture_format    = \n| audio_format      = \n| first_aired       = {{Start date|2012|02|01}}\n| last_aired        = present\n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n| related           = \n| website           = https://www.tlc.com/tv-shows/my-600-lb-life/\n| production_website = \n}}\n'''''My 600-lb Life''''' is a [[reality television]] series that has aired on the [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] television network since 2012. Each episode follows a year in the life of morbidly [[obese]] individuals, who begin the episode weighing at least {{convert|600|lb}}, and documents their attempts to reduce their weight to a healthy level. Update episodes, called \"Where Are They Now?\", feature one or more previous patients, picking up a year or more after their original episodes aired.\n\nPatients are placed under the care of Iranian-American [[Houston]] surgeon [[Younan Nowzaradan]] (often referred to as simply \"Dr. Now\"), who first has them attempt losing weight on their own by following a strict [[diet (nutrition)|diet]], and then depending on the patient's progress may offer [[gastric bypass surgery]] or [[sleeve gastrectomy]] to further assist in [[weight loss]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/bodies/my-600-lb-life-dr-nowzaradan-why-difficult-patients-keep-weight-off/ | title=My 600-Lb. Life Dr. Nowzaradan on Why It\u2019s Difficult for Patients to Keep the Weight Off | work=People | date=May 30, 2017 | accessdate=November 18, 2017 | author=King, Brittany}}</ref>\n\n==Concept==\nThis series was originally a five-part [[miniseries]] involving four morbidly obese patients. Because of its popularity, new episodes were filmed, including a \"Where Are They Now?\" retrospective in Season 4 that follows up on previous patients to track their weight-loss journey months or years after [[bariatric surgery]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/27/my-600-lb-life-where-are-they-now-video_n_1381855.html|title=\u2018My 600-lb Life: Where are They Now?\u2019: Have They Kept The Weight Off?|date=March 27, 2012|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Season 1, patients were filmed over a period of seven years (2004\u20132011). Beginning with Season 2, patients were filmed for only one year. In Season 8, certain patients' stories were filmed for only six months. \n\nBeginning with Season 5, new episodes began filming as 2-hour episodes instead of 1-hour. This was previously done with Melissa's Story (split into two parts) and Lupe's Story. Recap episodes titled under \"Supersized\" and \"Extended\", which include additional facts and footage respectively, also aired during this season.\n\n==Subject outcomes==\nSeven patients have died since appearing on the show.\n\n* Henry Foots, who was featured in season one, died of an illness unrelated to his weight loss surgery on May 16, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|via=Legacy.com|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/henry-foots-obituary?pid=1000000164888383|title=Henry Foots Obituary|accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* Sean Milliken, who was chronicled on the fourth season of the show, died on February 17, 2019, from an infection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/health/my-600-lb-life-sean-milliken-dead/|title=My 600-Lb. Life Star Sean Milliken Is Dead at Age 29|website=people.com|accessdate=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n* LB Bonner, who was featured on the sixth season of the show, died by suicide on August 2, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2018/08/lb-bonner-dead-my-600-pound-life/|title=\u2018My 600-Lb Life\u2019 Star L.B. Bonner Dead At 30|date=Aug 3, 2018|accessdate=Feb 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* Lisa Fleming, also a third sixth season participant, died on August 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|work=US Weekly|title=\u2018My 600-lb Life\u2019 Star Lisa Fleming Dead at 50|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/lisa-fleming-dead-my-600-lb-life-star-dies-at-50/|author=Hearon, Sarah|date=August 24, 2018|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n* Rob Buchel was featured in season six and suffered a fatal heart attack on November 15, 2017, during filming of the show, while staying in a skilled nursing facility in Houston.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bever|first1=Lindsey|title=A \u2018My 600-lb Life\u2019 participant died while filming his fight to lose weight|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2018/03/02/a-my-600-lb-life-participant-died-while-filming-his-fight-to-lose-weight/|website=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 3, 2018|date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Buchel's death was the first in the series to be featured during the patient's respective episode.\n* Kelly Mason, a participant on the show's seventh season, died on February 15, 2019, from heart failure. Mason's death was the second in the series to be featured during the patient's respective episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5364122/kelly-my-600-lb-life-dies-heart-failure|title=Kelly Mason Becomes Second \u2018My 600-LB Life\u2019 Subject To Die During Show\u2019s Filming, Suffering Heart Failure|publisher=Inqisitr|accessdate=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n* James King, a participant on the show's fifth season, died on April 3, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milnerandorr.com/obituaries/James-D-King?obId=12614275#/obituaryInfo|title=James D. King|publisher=Milner & Orr|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\nSusan Farmer, who appeared in an episode on the show's third season, notably faced [[neuropathy]] as a result of her weight, which was profiled on the show.<ref>{{cite web|work=metro.co.uk|title=Woman whose weight left her temporarily paralysed loses 19 stone and learns to walk again|url=https://metro.co.uk/2015/04/09/woman-whose-weight-left-her-temporarily-paralysed-loses-19-stone-and-learns-to-walk-again-5141483/|date=April 9, 2015|accessdate=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==Spin off==\nBeginning in January 2015, TLC began airing ''[[List of My 600-lb Life episodes#Where Are They Now? (2015-present)|My 600-lb Life: Where Are They Now?]]''. The purpose of this spin off was to update viewers on the weight loss journeys of people featured on previous seasons.  As of 2018, five seasons of the ''Where Are They Now?'' follow-ups have aired.\n\n== Lawsuit ==\nIn 2020, it was reported by several news outlets that several former patients of Dr. Nowzardan who appeared on the series, and the family of one patient, L. B. Bonner, who died by suicide, had brought suit against the show's production company, Megalomedia, alleging negligence and claiming that the company failed to cover medical costs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theashleysrealityroundup.com/2020/02/27/three-more-my-600-lb-life-cast-members-file-lawsuits-against-shows-production-company-their-lawyer-says-they-intend-to-end-this-show/|title=Three More \u2018My 600 Lb Life\u2019 Cast Members File Lawsuits Against Show\u2019s Production Company; Their Lawyer Says They \u201cIntend to End This Show\u201d|date=2020-02-27|website=The Ashley's Reality Roundup|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehollywoodgossip.com/2020/02/my-600-lb-life-sued-by-four-former-stars-end-this-show-now/|title=My 600-lb Life Sued by FOUR Former Stars: End This Show, NOW!|last=Delott|first=Simon|date=2020-02-28|website=The Hollywood Gossip|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{main|List of My 600-lb Life episodes}}\n{{:List of My 600-lb Life episodes}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\"\n|+ Season 1\n! Ep\n! style=\"background:#FFE4E1\" |Patient Name\n! Starting Age\n! Location\n! Starting Weight\n! Ending Weight (7 yrs)\n! Total Weight Loss (7 yrs.)\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1/2 || Melissa Morris || 31 years old ||Livingston, TX || {{convert|653|lb}} || {{convert|206|lb}} \n|{{convert|447|lb}}||\n|-\n|3 || Donald Shelton || 34 years old || Pasadena, TX || {{convert|675|lb}} || {{convert|390|lb}}\n|{{convert|285|lb}}||\n|-\n|4 || Henry Foots || 47 years old || Houston, TX || {{convert|715|lb}} || {{convert|275|lb}}\n|{{convert|440|lb}}|| Deceased, age 54\n|-\n|5 || Ashley Randall || 24 years old || Killeen, TX || {{convert|617|lb}} || {{convert|253.1|lb}}\n|{{convert|364|lb}}||\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\"\n|+ Season 2\n! Ep\n! style=\"background:#B0E0E6\" | Patient Name\n! Starting Age\n! Location\n! Starting Weight\n! Ending Weight (12 mos.)\n! Total Weight Loss (12 mos. or from later peak weight)\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || Zsalynn Whitworth || 42 years old || 